      "text": "A photon can (but does not have to) have a \"polarization direction\". It then [[oscillate]]s in a plane on which the beam direction lies. The [[Oscillation]] is a sine curve, the exact properties of which are not of interest for the purposes of this book. Only the plane itself is of interest. We can imagine it as a glass plate in which the photon is trapped. Figs. 2.3 and 2.4 show the situation when a polarized photon is emitted from the photon box."
